[1
Date: 28 Apr 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Monitor (Kampala), 10 April 2001

A councillor in Entebbe, [Uganda, Ssewali Kalule, [told the Municipal
Council that Wakiso district needs 2 tonnes of mosaic-free cassava in order
to fight the virus that has hit Entebbe. Kalule told "The Monitor" on 9
April that mosaic-free cassava [is needed to provide families with enough
food to improve their nutrition. She said Entebbe had been hit by the
virus and [that the crop, which is eaten by most families, has been
devastated by the disease.
Kalule said that Entebbe families depend on imported cassava chips from
Tanzania, Islands and other areas in the country.
"My office, this weekend (8 Apr 2001) distributed 3 sacks of cassava
cuttings, 60 kg of hybrid maize seeds, and Phia 17 type of bananas that can
multiply in a short period," she said.
[Byline: Kabona Esiara
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The delay in posting this report was because it took time to confirm the
identity of the virus causing the disease. The disease is probably caused
by the 'Ugandan variant' (UgV), a begomovirus with properties of African
cassava mosaic virus and East African cassava mosaic virus. Cassava is a
major staple in the diet of Ugandans and severe losses in the crop can have
grave consequences for the population. - Mod.DH
