[2
Date: 27 Apr 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Uganda National Cassava Programme (NCP), National Agricultural
Research Organisation [edited

Cassava mosaic virus disease (CMD) in [Uganda was first reported in the
1920s. The causal pathogen was recognized as African cassava mosaic
begomovirus (ACMV), which is transmitted by the whitefly, _Bemisia tabaci_.
There have been various reports of serious damage by the disease in the
country in the 1920s and 1940s. These were contained by introduction of
resistant varieties.
CMD [occurs wherever cassava [_Manihot esculenta_ is grown in Uganda, but
[the disease remained endemic for decades until the late 1980s, when [an
epidemic was noted about 100 km north of Kampala. Unusually severe CMD
symptoms and very high whitefly populations were [associated with the
epidemic. [CMD was associated with a new virus strain, commonly referred
to as the 'Uganda Variant' (UgV), [which has properties of both ACMV and
East African cassava mosaic virus (EACMV), another virus [found mainly on
the East African coast and Madagascar.
[Cassava infected with both ACMV and UgV exhibits more severe symptoms.
The epidemic [moved southwards at a rate of about 20-30 km per year,
[reaching Kampala by 1997 and most of the areas on the shores of Lake
Victoria by 1998. [By 1999, except for isolated pockets of the country,
most parts of Uganda [and neighboring countries had been [affected by the
epidemic. [Cassava production virtually ceased [because most of the
varieties grown by the farmers proved very susceptible to the disease. It
is estimated that over 500 local genotypes were lost to the disease, with a
net result of food shortages and famine.
[Attempts are being made to restore cassava production in [Uganda, mainly
through developing, multiplying, and distributing CMD-resistant cassava
varieties. NARO has developed and released 12 CMD-resistant varieties, but
the task of making these and others available to farmers who need them
remains enormous. In Uganda today, the increased importance of cassava both
as a food security strategy and source of cash income for the rural poor
[cannot be over-emphasised. The National Cassava Program (NCP) has the
national mandate for research and development of the crop, with a goal of
contributing to the well-being of the people of [Uganda.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[EACMV is present in Kenya, Madagascar, Malawi, Tanzania, Zimbabwe, and
possibly in Zambia and Mozambique; ACMV is found primarily in Angola,
Kenya, Nigeria, and the Seychelles. Molecular studies show that UgV is a
recombinant virus containing a large part of the ACMV coat protein gene,
which has been inserted into the DNA-A of an EACMV-like sequence. Famine in
1994 caused by UgV infection of cassava was associated with the deaths of
3000 people. Before the epidemic, annual cassava production in Uganda was
about 3.5 million metric tonnes (mt), but it dropped to about 0.5 million
mt after the outbreak of UgV infection.
Useful references:
<http://www.idrc.ca/reports/read_article_english.cfm?article_num=558>
<http://vir.sgmjournals.org/cgi/reprint/78/8/2101>
Contacts:
