[3
Date: 21 May 2001
From: Dick Hamilton <rihamilto@home.com>
Source: British Soc Plant Pathol, New Disease Reports Vol. 3 [edited
[The following is derived from the above source, in an article by JP Legg
and colleagues, entitled: Spread into Rwanda of the severe cassava mosaic
virus disease pandemic and associated Uganda variant of East African
cassava mosaic virus (EACMV-Ug).

Cassava (_Manihot esculenta_) is a major food staple in the Great Lakes
zone of East and Central Africa. During the 1990s a devastating pandemic
caused by the emerging Ugandan variant of East African cassava mosaic
begomovirus (EACMV-Ug) spread through Uganda and into neighboring Kenya and
Tanzania. A survey was initiated in July 2000 to determine the presence or
absence of severe cassava mosaic disease (CMD) and EACMV-Ug. 26 farmers'
cassava fields were assessed in the major cassava-producing areas of the
country. At each site, assessments were made of CMD incidence, severity
(2-5), and infection type (whitefly- or cutting-borne), and leaf samples
were collected from 2 symptomatic plants for virus diagnosis. A standard
polymerase chain reaction (PCR) diagnostic procedure was employed in which
specific primer pairs for African cassava mosaic begomovirus (ACMV) and
EACMV-Ug were used for detection.
The incidence of CMD was low (about 27%) and no clear differences were
observed between administrative regions. However, disease severity was
highest (score 3.6) in the Umatara administrative region, compared with 2.4
in other regions. In Umatara, most infection was whitefly-borne (83%) while
in other regions it was mainly due to cutting-borne infection (81%).
EACMV-Ug was detected in 26 samples, all from Umatara. One plant was
infected with EACMV-Ug and ACMV. Mean severity scores from virus-tested
plants were: ACMV (2.9), EACMV-Ug (4.O), ACMV + EACMV-Ug (5.0).
These data provide evidence for the recent spread into Rwanda of the
EACMV-Ug-associated pandemic of severe CMD, probably mediated through
migration of viruliferous whiteflies from Uganda and/or Tanzania.
Consequently, there is an urgent need for CMD control through deployment of
resistant cultivars, as has been done in Uganda, Kenya, and Tanzania.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[According to Zhou and colleqgues (J Gen Virol 1997; 78: 2101-11,
EACMV-UgvV appears to have arisen by interspecific recombination of EACMV
and ACMV. There is no question that infection by the UgV strain and other
viruses is compromising food security in Rwanda and, indeed, other
countries in the Great Lakes zone. Though development of pest-resistant
cultivars by the International Institute of Tropical Agriculture is a
positive step, deployment of these cultivars is critical to curb losses in
cassava and other food crops in the region. Unfortunately, the human
tragedy is invisible to the world at large. According to a posting by
on 18 May 2001, operations of the World Food Program (WFP)
in Rwanda have been hampered by a serious shortage of food commodities
during April. Some nutrition centers have been forced to provide smaller
portions of food for therapeutic- and supplementary-feeding programs.
During April WFP-Rwanda distributed 1094 metric tonnes of food to 86 634
people. The complete WFP story can be obtained from the following web site:
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200105180018.html>
The reference to the paper by Zhou et al. can be obtained at:
<http://vir.sgmjournals.org/cgi/reprint/78/8/2101.pdf>
- Mod.DH
