[4
Date: 21 May 2001
From: Dick Hamilton <rihamilto@home.com>
Source: Titus Alicai <talicai@hotmail.com> [edited

The history of cassava mosaic virus disease (CMD) in [Uganda goes back to
the 1920s when the disease was first reported in the country. The causal
pathogen was recognised as African cassava mosaic [begomovirus (ACMV). [In
the 1920s and 1940s there were reports of serious [crop losses that were
contained by introduction of resistant varieties.
Since then, CMD [occurred wherever cassava [was grown in Uganda but
remained endemic for decades until the late 1980s when a resurgence of the
epidemic was noted about 100 km north of Kampala. Unusually severe CMD
symptoms, very high whitefly populations, and a new virus strain, now
commonly referred to as the 'Uganda Variant' (UgV), [were associated with
the epidemic. UgV has properties of both ACMV and East African cassava
mosaic virus EACMV), another strain of the virus whose distribution [is
mainly on the East African coast and Madagascar.
Other studies have shown that more severe symptoms arise from dual
infections of ACMV and UgV. The epidemic [expanded southwards in a
front-like formation at a rate of about 20-30 km per year. It reached
Kampala by 1997 and most of the areas on the shores of lake Victoria (where
Entebbe lies) by 1998. [By 1999, except for isolated pockets of the
country, most parts of Uganda had [were affected by the epidemic and
similar conditions [were reported in neighbouring countries. [The
pandemic brought cassava production in the country to a near halt,
[because most varieties grown by farmers [were very susceptible to the
disease. It is estimated that over 500 local genotypes were lost to the
disease, [causing food shortages and famine.
It should be noted that [CMD is not an entirely new or
very-recently-re-emerged problem, except [in those areas [that were
affected by the epidemic later than others. [Efforts are being made to
further to understand the [disease and to restore cassava production in
the country. This has mainly been through developing, multiplying and
distributing CMD-resistant cassava varieties. As a response to the
pandemic, NARO has developed and released 12 CMD-resistant varieties, but
the task of [providing these and others to farmers who need them remains
enormous.
In Uganda today, the increased importance of cassava both as [an element
the strategy for food security and source of cash income for the rural
poor [cannot be overemphasised. The NCP has the national mandate for
research and development of the crop with a goal of making contributions to
the well-being of the people of [Uganda.
--
